Mars Lithology Scout (MLS-1) 'Red Badger'

Type: robotic | Generated: 12/6/2025

Executive Summary

A compact, autonomous six-wheeled rover designed for geological exploration, core sampling, and in-situ analysis on the Martian surface. It features a high-mobility suspension system and a collapsible form factor to fit within standard landing payload envelopes.

Generated Implementation (cpp)

#include 

// Hardware Pin Definitions (Mockup)
#define HEATER_PIN 10
#define DRILL_ARM_PIN 11
#define SOLAR_DEPLOY_PIN 12

// Rover Operational States
enum RoverState {
  STOWED,      // Folded within 1m^3 envelope
  DEPLOYING,   // Unfolding solar arrays and suspension
  IDLE,        // Standing by for commands
  DRIVING,     // 6-wheel locomotion active
  DRILLING,    // In-situ analysis active
  SAFE_MODE    // Thermal or power critical
};

class MartianRover {
private:
  RoverState currentState;
  float batteryVoltage;
  float internalTemp;
  
  // Thermal constraints
  const float MIN_OP_TEMP = -40.0; // Heaters on below this
  const float MAX_OP_TEMP = 30.0;  // Passive cooling/stop ops above this
  const float CRITICAL_LOW = -120.0;

  void manageThermalSystem() {
    // Basic hysteresis loop for thermal survival
    if (internalTemp < MIN_OP_TEMP) {
      digitalWrite(HEATER_PIN, HIGH);
    } else {
      digitalWrite(HEATER_PIN, LOW);
    }
  }

  void controlSixWheelDrive(float throttle, float steering) {
    // Simplified differential drive logic for 6 wheels
    // In a real Rocker-Bogie, this would calculate corner steering angles
    int leftPwm = constrain((throttle + steering) * 255, -255, 255);
    int rightPwm = constrain((throttle - steering) * 255, -255, 255);
    
    // Apply to motor drivers (pseudo-function)
    // setMotorGroup(LEFT_SIDE, leftPwm);
    // setMotorGroup(RIGHT_SIDE, rightPwm);
  }

public:
  MartianRover() : currentState(STOWED), batteryVoltage(28.0), internalTemp(-20.0) {}

  void init() {
    pinMode(HEATER_PIN, OUTPUT);
    pinMode(DRILL_ARM_PIN, OUTPUT);
    pinMode(SOLAR_DEPLOY_PIN, OUTPUT);
  }

  // Main control loop called by void loop()
  void update(float currentTemp, float currentVolts) {
    internalTemp = currentTemp;
    batteryVoltage = currentVolts;
    
    manageThermalSystem();

    // State Machine Logic
    switch (currentState) {
      case STOWED:
        // Waiting for landing confirmation signal to deploy
        break;
        
      case DEPLOYING:
        // Execute timed sequence to release constraints
        digitalWrite(SOLAR_DEPLOY_PIN, HIGH);
        // Check limit switches (mock logic)
        if (millis() > 10000) { 
          currentState = IDLE;
          digitalWrite(SOLAR_DEPLOY_PIN, LOW);
        }
        break;
        
      case DRIVING:
        // Locomotion logic handled via external command inputs
        break;
        
      case DRILLING:
        // 5-DOF Arm and Percussive Drill logic
        // Ensure wheels are locked
        controlSixWheelDrive(0, 0);
        digitalWrite(DRILL_ARM_PIN, HIGH);
        break;
        
      case SAFE_MODE:
        // Minimize power usage, wait for recharge or thermal stabilization
        controlSixWheelDrive(0, 0);
        digitalWrite(DRILL_ARM_PIN, LOW);
        break;
    }
  }

  void receiveCommand(String cmd, float val1, float val2) {
    if (currentState == SAFE_MODE && cmd != "RESET") return;

    if (cmd == "DEPLOY") {
      if (currentState == STOWED) currentState = DEPLOYING;
    } else if (cmd == "DRIVE") {
      currentState = DRIVING;
      controlSixWheelDrive(val1, val2);
    } else if (cmd == "DRILL") {
      currentState = DRILLING;
    } else if (cmd == "STOP") {
      currentState = IDLE;
      controlSixWheelDrive(0, 0);
      digitalWrite(DRILL_ARM_PIN, LOW);
    }
  }
};

MartianRover rover;

void setup() {
  rover.init();
}

void loop() {
  // Read sensors (mock values)
  float temp = -35.0; 
  float volts = 24.5;
  rover.update(temp, volts);
  delay(100);
}

Validation Checks

  • Parts List Inconsistency: The 'Diagrams Plan' and 'Assembly Steps' reference a 'Sensing Mast' (or MastCam) and a 'High-Gain Antenna', but these components are missing from the 'Parts List'.
  • Physical/Dimension Logic: The 'Deployable Solar Array' is listed as 'Quantity: 2' with '2.5m diameter deployed'. Two arrays of this size would result in a rover width >5m, which is disproportionate for a 1m^3 stowed 'compact' rover (<180kg). It implies a single array system or a smaller individual size.
  • Constraint Logic: The battery capacity of '100Ah' is likely too heavy for a 180kg solar-powered rover class (historically MER rovers were ~185kg with ~16Ah batteries). While modern density is higher, 100Ah pushes the weight limit significantly.
  • Assembly Logic: 'Install solar panel deployment hinges' is listed, but the solar array part itself implies a singular stowage. Clarification on the single vs dual array structure is needed in the parts list.
